<h2>Your First CSS Code</h2>
<p>
    Before we get started writing CSS code, it’s important to know how colors work in CSS.  There are a few different ways for you to tell the computer which color that you want to use.  You can just type the name of a color in English when specifying the color, but this doesn’t work for most colors and you can’t get the exact color that you want.  Usually, you’ll want to either give the computer a hex value (short for hexadecimal value) or and RGB value (short for Red-Blue-Green value).
</p>

<p>
    RGB and hex values look like this: rgb(34,253,201) and #AA1111
</p>

<p>
    Hex values and RGB values can both represent any color that the computer can display, and you can get as creative with your color mixes as you want!  In our code we’re going to use RGB values.  RGB values are three numbers that correspond to the amount of red, blue, and green in a color on a scale from 0 to 255.  Once you understand how RGB and hex values work you can change them without using a color value generator, but we’re going to use one in these exercises.
</p>

<p>
    Here’s the link to a color value generator:https://www.w3schools.com/colors/colors_picker.asp
    There are tons of these online, we just selected this one at random.  Feel free to use any color generator that you like.
</p>

<p>
